| 8 | [Panaca Summit Archeological District](/Panaca_Summit_Archeological_District) | Upload image | March 19, 1990 (#90000362) | Address Restricted [Panaca](/Panaca,_Nevada) | The [Panaca Summit Archeological District](/Panaca_Summit_Archeological_District) near [Panaca](/Panaca,_Nevada) is another one of those places where the past is so fragile, it must be shielded from the present. Its address is, predictably, restricted, a necessary measure to protect the invaluable remnants of ancient human habitation. Discovered and subsequently listed in 1990, this district encompasses a rich tapestry of prehistoric sites, offering archaeologists and historians a window into the lives of early inhabitants of the Great Basin. These sites often contain evidence of hunting, gathering, and spiritual practices, allowing us to piece together the complex narratives of cultures that thrived and vanished long before written records. It's a silent library of human endurance, best left undisturbed by the casual passerby. |
| 9 | [Pioche Firehouse](/Pioche_Firehouse) | [Pioche Firehouse](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Pioche_Firehouse.jpg/100px-Pioche_Firehouse.jpg) | February 5, 2018 (#100002070) | Lots 3 & 32, Block 1 of Pioche Townsite, N of Main St. & Lacour • 37°55′47″N 114°27′06″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;37.929835°N 114.451652°W&#xfeff; / 37.929835; -114.451652&#xfeff; ([Pioche Firehouse](/Pioche_Firehouse)) [Pioche](/Pioche,_Nevada) | In a town prone to both literal and metaphorical conflagrations, a firehouse was not merely a convenience; it was a necessity. The [Pioche Firehouse](/Pioche_Firehouse), located north of Main Street and Lacour within the original townsite, was listed in 2018, acknowledging its role in protecting the community from the ever-present threat of fire, a common scourge in early mining towns built largely of wood. Beyond its functional purpose, it represents the collective effort and organization required to sustain a community in a challenging environment. It's a symbol of civic responsibility, a reminder that even in the pursuit of mineral wealth, some things are worth saving from the flames. |
| 10 | [Smith Hotel-Cornelius Hotel](/Smith_Hotel-Cornelius_Hotel) | [Smith Hotel-Cornelius Hotel](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Cornelius_Hotel_Caliente_NV.jpg/100px-Cornelius_Hotel_Caliente_NV.jpg) | June 10, 2008 (#08000510) | 100 Spring St. • 37°36′56″N 114°30′39″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;37.615556°N 114.510833°W&#xfeff; / 37.615556; -114.510833&#xfeff; ([Smith Hotel-Cornelius Hotel](/Smith_Hotel-Cornelius_Hotel)) [Caliente](/Caliente,_Nevada) | The building known as the [Smith Hotel-Cornelius Hotel](/Smith_Hotel-Cornelius_Hotel) at 100 Spring Street in [Caliente](/Caliente,_Nevada) is a testament to the persistent need for rest and lodging, even in the most unforgiving of landscapes. Hotels, particularly in early 20th-century frontier towns, were not just places to sleep; they were social hubs, temporary homes for travelers, miners, and railroad workers, echoing with countless stories of transient lives. This particular structure, listed in 2008, embodies the era's architectural styles and the economic vitality that once flowed through [Caliente](/Caliente,_Nevada) due to its railroad connection. It stands as a silent witness to the ebb and flow of human movement, offering a glimpse into the transient nature of life on the move. |
| 11 | [White River Narrows Archeological District](/Weepah_Spring_Wilderness) | [White River Narrows Archeological District](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/White_River_Narrows_Petroglyphs.jpg/100px-White_River_Narrows_Petroglyphs.jpg) | August 1, 1978 (#78001723) | [Weepah Spring Wilderness](/Weepah_Spring_Wilderness) Address Restricted [Hiko](/Hiko,_Nevada) | Like its Black Canyon counterpart, the [White River Narrows Archeological District](/Weepah_Spring_Wilderness) is a treasure trove of ancient history, nestled within the expansive [Weepah Spring Wilderness](/Weepah_Spring_Wilderness) near [Hiko](/Hiko,_Nevada). This district, with its predictably restricted address, protects an extensive collection of petroglyphs and other archaeological features, offering an unparalleled record of human presence in the region spanning thousands of years. The sheer volume and diversity of the rock art here provide anthropologists with crucial insights into the cultural practices, cosmology, and social structures of the various groups who once called this land home. Its inscription on the Register in 1978 signifies its profound scientific and cultural importance, a silent library of human history etched into the very bones of the earth. |

